    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-03-18T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-03-18T22:00:00-05:00" n="773"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d773">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">603.002/1000: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-03-19T10:00:00+07:00"
                            >March 19, 1940—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>134. Department’s 28, February 29, 3 p.m.<note n="50" xml:id="d773fn50">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_504">p. 504</ref>.</note> My
                    115, March 7, noon. British Embassy in its note addressed to Minister of Finance
                    not only requested Kung to offer no opposition to reopening of customhouses at
                    Chinkiang and Nanking but to send no instructions to Maze on the subject. French
                    Embassy in its note limited action to request that China offer no opposition to
                    reopening of offices mentioned. Kung has now addressed similar letters to
                    British and French Ambassadors and to me, text of which I quote in separate
                        message.<note n="51" xml:id="d773fn51">
                        <hi rend="italic">Infra</hi>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping and Shanghai. Peiping please air mail to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
